A BBC journalist arrested by Egyptian police in Cairo has been released, the corporation said on Tuesday.Shaimaa Khalil was detained on Monday after soldiers and riot police cleared a three-week sit-in in Tahrir Square in the Egyptian capital.Kevin Bakhurst, controller of the BBC News channel and deputy head of the BBC newsroom, said on Twitter: "BBC - A BBC producer who was arrested by Egyptian police in Cairo has been released. Shaimaa Khalil was arrested in Tahrir Square on Monday.""I'm and ppl with me ok on way to see 28 mil prosecutor," Khalil tweeted on Tuesday, a reference to a military prosecution and court complex in Cairo.Khalil had earlier tweeted: "#Tahrir now ... surrounded by military, riot police and armoured vehicles. extremely tens ... #Tahrir main ring now. 'careful!' someone just told me. 'they arrest anyone taking photos.' "Witnesses told the AFP news agency that demonstrators were beaten and that people had their mobile phones taken and were warned not to take photographs.The corporation had said it was "very concerned" by her arrest. "She is a fine journalist, simply doing her job. We are doing all we can to secure her release," it said in a statement.The BBC's foreign editor, Jon Williams, said on Twitter: "Arresting journalists for doing job not great advert for new Egypt.""Very concerned at the detention of Shaimaa Khalil in Cairo – a good journalist doing her job," he said . "Doing all we can to secure her release."Khalil's arrest follows concerns over the renewed harassment of the media in the aftermath of the overthrow of ousted president Hosni Mubarak.• To contact the MediaGuardian news desk email editor@mediatheguardian.com or phone 020 3353 3857. For all other inquiries please call the main Guardian switchboard on 020 3353 2000. If you are writing a comment for publication, please mark clearly "for publication".• To get the latest media news to your desktop or mobile, follow MediaGuardian on Twitter and Facebook.